      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydration/hydrolysis under alkaline conditions converts the phosphoroaminonitrile into the corresponding phosphoramidic acid species.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied literature explicitly states that phosphoroaminonitriles hydrolyze at pH 13 to N-phosphoramidic acids. This step is therefore directly imposed from the literature-guided phosphoro-Strecker framework (Closs et al., 2020; Liu et al., 2019; sources 21192, 21193 summarized in KB findings).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface H2S conversion of phosphoro intermediate to threonine aminothioamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"near-neutral pH ~7 with dissolved H2S\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sulfur incorporation transforms the activated phosphoroaminonitrile manifold into an aminothioamide branch.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature summary explicitly notes conversion of phosphoroaminonitrile intermediates with H2S at pH 7 to aminothioamides. This provides a second experimentally motivated branch from the phosphoro-Strecker node toward threonine-related products (Closs et al., 2020; Liu et al., 2019; sources 21192, 21193 summarized in KB findings).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-style assembly of 2-oxobutanoic acid from glyoxylate and acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",