 marked as a literature-motivated extrapolation necessary to complete the target network (Barge et al., 2019; source 1026; source 6987/6944 summarized in KB findings).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile and phosphoro/thioamide precursors to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling, variable pH including acidic episodes around pH 1.5 for aminonitrile release\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolysis of aminonitrile, phosphoramidic acid, and thioamide derivatives yields the free amino acid threonine, with phosphate released from phosphoro intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This endpoint combines the literature-supported hydrolytic fates of Strecker and phosphoro-Strecker intermediates. The supplied report explicitly notes aminonitrile formation at low pH ~1.5 in the phosphoro-Strecker manifold and hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids in classic Strecker chemistry. Dry-wet cycling is included because the literature also highlights such cycling as relevant to prebiotic amino-acid processing and assembly (Closs et al., 2020; Liu et al., 2019; Strecker, 1850; sources 21192, 21193, 6940, 512 summarized in KB findings).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal aldehyde to ketoacid to threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent-derived acetaldehyde and glyoxylate converge through a C4 \u03b1-ketoacid intermediate, followed by abiotic amination to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal fixed carbon via formate to glyoxylate route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 reduction first yields formate, then glyoxylate/pyruvate, feeding the \u03b1-ketoacid route to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface UV cyanide-enabled ketoacid amination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde is photochemically converted to cyanide-bearing surface feedstocks, supporting subsequent \u03b1-ketoacid amination to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic glyoxylate branch to threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic chemistry generates glyoxylate from formaldehyde and HCN, then proceeds through the \u03b1-ketoacid route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct phosphoro-Strecker to phosphoramidic acid to threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface acetaldehyde enters the DAP-mediated phosphoro-Strecker network, then hydrolyzes through the phosphoramidic acid branch to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct phosphoro-Strecker thioamide branch to threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"DAP-mediated threonine precursor formation diverges into an H2S-driven aminothioamide route before final hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Ketoacid route with aminonitrile capture\",\n      \"description\": \"The \u03b1-ketoacid precursor 2-oxobutanoate is aminated in the presence of ammonia and cyanide to threonine aminonitrile, then hydrolyzed to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface integrated Strecker-like target route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal aldehydes feed a surface cyanide network, then a biochemical hydrolysis step yields threonine through aminonitrile intermediacy.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-supported integrated phosphoro-Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 fixation to formate supports hydrothermal carbonyl production; acetaldehyde then enters the phosphoro-Strecker manifold and hydrolyzes to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic-glyoxylate plus phosphoro-Strecker hybrid route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface HCN/H2S chemistry and the DAP-mediated phosphoro-Strecker route operate in parallel, converging through hydrolytic release of threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_019\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_016\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "This network targets threonine through a connected prebiotic graph that links hydrothermal carbon fixation and aldehyde generation to surface cyanide chemistry and final biochemical-style assembly. Because the literature specifically supports Strecker chemistry, phosphoro-Strecker chemistry, abiotic \u03b1-ketoacid conversion, hydrothermal synthesis contexts, cyanosulfidic/surface-UV precursor generation, and dry-wet peptide-forming settings, the network uses these as the primary routes. Convergence is centered on formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, HCN, glyoxylate, and 2-oxobutanoic acid as hub intermediates. Ten distinct pathways to threonine are represented by different combinations of hydrothermal precursor formation, surface aminonitrile generation, phosphoro-Strecker branching, \u03b1-ketoacid assembly, and final hydrolysis/transamination steps.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formate/formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "CH5N3O2P", "iupac_name": "diamidophosphoric acid", "common_name": "diamidophosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "sulfane", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H4N2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanenitrile", "common_name": "alanine aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H6N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C4H6O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "2-ketobutyric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O3/c1-2-3(5)4(6)7/h2H2,1H3,(H,6,7)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C4H7N2O3P", "iupac_name": "N-phosphoro-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "N-phosphoroaminonitrile of threonine", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H10NO6P", "iupac_name": "N-phosphoro-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "N-phosphoramidic acid precursor to threonine", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C4H9NOS", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanethioamide", "common_name": "threonine aminothioamide", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "H3PO4", "iupac_name": "phosphoric acid", "common_name": "phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite", "mackinawite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 through Fe-S mediated electron transfer to give formate.", "reasoning": "Directly follows the reported hydrothermal vent framework where greigite and related Fe-S phases reduce CO2 to formate under alkaline, H2-rich conditions; this is a standard prebiotic carbon-fixation entry point linked to vent chemistry and lower-temperature alkaline systems relevant to amino-acid precursor synthesis (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Cody et al., 2000; Russell & Martin, 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type formation of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "elemental iron"], "conditions": {"temperature": "360-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic hydrothermal/subseafloor setting; FTT-type carbon hydrogenation"}, "mechanism": "Successive CO2/CO hydrogenation on magnetite/Fe0 surfaces generates reduced C1-C2 carbonyl compounds including formaldehyde and acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "The literature report specifically identifies magnetite as the best-supported mineral catalyst for prebiotic FTT chemistry, producing primordial organics from reduced carbon feedstocks; acetaldehyde and formaldehyde are plausible carbonyl outputs needed for Strecker and carbon-backbone extension chemistry feeding threonine synthesis (McCollom, 2013; Cody et al., 2000; sources summarized in KB results on magnetite and FTT chemistry)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal generation of glyoxylate and pyruvate from fixed carbon", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite", "pyrite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic hydrothermal circulation; protometabolic carbon-fixation context"}, "mechanism": "Surface-mediated carbonyl coupling and redox equilibration convert reduced C1 inputs into \u03b1-ketoacids including glyoxylate and pyruvate.", "reasoning": "The knowledge base specifically identifies glyoxylate and pyruvate as prebiotically relevant precursor molecules and protometabolic hubs connected to amino-acid formation. Exact stepwise mineral-specific yields are not established for threonine synthesis, so this reaction is a necessary connecting abstraction grounded in hydrothermal protometabolic \u03b1-ketoacid chemistry and marked as a literature-supported but network-level simplification (Muchowska et al., 2020; Keller et al., 2014; sources 995, 9332, 9334 summarized in KB findings)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface UV production of HCN and formamide from formaldehyde feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated shallow pools, anoxic, evaporation-concentration cycles"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical oxidation-reduction and nitrile-forming chemistry generate cyanide-bearing feedstocks and formamide from reduced carbon and nitrogen sources.", "reasoning": "The research summary explicitly lists surface/UV chemistry, HCN chemistry, and formamide-producing photochemistry as plausible prebiotic routes relevant to amino-acid/nucleobase precursor formation, though not uniquely specific to threonine. This step is included as a literature-grounded connector to supply HCN for Strecker and phosphoro-Strecker routes (Sutherland, 2016; Patel et al., 2015; Ferris & Hagan, 1984; sources 21187, 9381, 9382, 6942 summarized in KB findings)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Cyanosulfidic conversion of formaldehyde to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-driven cyanosulfidic chemistry in shallow surface waters"}, "mechanism": "HCN-derived and sulfide-assisted photoredox chemistry channels C1 carbonyls into more oxidized C2 species such as glyoxylate.", "reasoning": "The literature summary specifically names cyanosulfidic chemistry, glycolonitrile-derived networks, bisulfite/sulfur intermediates, and glyoxylate as relevant precursor chemistry, even if a direct one-step threonine route is unresolved. This reaction represents a concise literature-based connection to the glyoxylate hub (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; sources 9381, 9382, 16400 summarized in KB findings)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface Strecker synthesis of alanine aminonitrile from acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic pool or tidal-flat concentration, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, cyanide adds to the iminium carbon, producing an aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "The Strecker reaction is one of the best-suppor