reonine, unless a hydroxy-substituted aldehyde or equivalent precursor is implied. The final hydrolysis node also pools multiple precursors into one step, which reduces clarity.', 'The alanine aminonitrile step is a strong and literature-consistent Strecker reaction, but it does not efficiently support threonine formation as presented. The pathway appears to use aminonitrile capture conceptually without a convincing conversion from alanine aminonitrile toward threonine. It therefore contains a good local reaction embedded in a weak global route.', 'The integrated hydrothermal-to-surface framing is sensible, but as described this route seems to jump from alanine-type Strecker chemistry into final threonine-producing hydrolysis without establishing the threonine-specific intermediate. That makes the pathway topologically connected but chemically incoherent for the target.', 'This hybrid route has a plausible hydrothermal feedstock origin and a literature-aligned phosphoro-Strecker ending, but the intermediate support from formate to later aldehyde-derived target chemistry is underdeveloped. The pathway is better than the pure ketoacid branches but still weakened by ambiguous carbon skeleton transfer into threonine-specific phosphoroaminonitrile formation.', 'This is a reasonably coherent hybrid route. The cyanosulfidic branch provides a plausible surface-chemistry context and the phosphoro-Strecker/thioamide branch is literature-supported. Still, glyoxylate does not clearly improve the threonine-specific route as currently drawn, and the final conversion remains too collapsed. Strong conceptually, but not fully rigorous.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network uses literature-grounded route classes rather than claiming a single threonine-specific proven synthesis.