mental route to 2-hydroxypropanal. This reaction is therefore marked as a constrained connector: it supplies the chemically appropriate hydroxyaldehyde precursor required for threonine-specific Strecker logic while remaining within the documented aldehyde/hydroxyaldehyde framework (Butlerow, 1861; Ricardo et al., 2004; Wolman et al., 1971).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface oxidation of pyruvate to hydroxypyruvate equivalents\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed shallow waters; cross-environment transfer from hydrothermal keto acids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical oxidation/rearrangement of protometabolic \u03b1-ketoacid pools gives hydroxy-keto intermediates feeding hydroxyaldehyde chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report emphasizes \u03b1-ketoacids such as pyruvate and glyoxylate as key prebiotic intermediates and notes surface/UV chemistry as relevant. This connector is included to couple hydrothermal protometabolism with surface hydroxy-carbonyl chemistry; it is plausible but less directly demonstrated than Strecker chemistry itself (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019; Barge et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from 2-hydroxypropanal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite/sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic aqueous pools; aldehyde-selective aminonitrile formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation between the hydroxyaldehyde and ammonia followed by cyanide addition yields the \u03b1-aminonitrile corresponding to threonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker reaction is one of the most strongly supported prebiotic amino-acid syntheses in the supplied literature. Applying it to a hydroxyaldehyde gives the correct threonine carbon skeleton through the aminonitrile intermediate. The route class is literature-supported, although direct threonine-specific yield data remain limited (Strecker, 1850; Cleaves, 2010; Powner et al., 2009 for prebiotic nitrile chemistry context).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker formation of N-phosphoro-threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"near-neutral pH ~7; aldehyde-selective phosphoro-Strecker conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Diamidophosphate activates the aldehyde/HCN manifold to form an N-phosphoroaminonitrile under neutral conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This follows the phosphoro-Strecker chemistry identified explicitly in the research summary: aldehyde + DAP + HCN at pH 7 gives N-phosphoroaminonitriles selectively from aldehydes. Using 2-hydroxypropanal supplies the threonine carbon skeleton while retaining the documented route class (Krishnamurthy et al., 2018; Muchowska et al., 2020 as broader phosphate-enabled prebiotic context).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"H2S-mediated conversion of N-phosphoroaminonitrile to aminothioamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH ~7 with dissolved H2S\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sulfur-mediated conversion of the phosphoroaminonitrile to the corresponding aminothioamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The supplied literature specifically states that phosphoro-Strecker intermediates react with H2S at pH 7 to form aminothioamides. This is one of the most direct literature-grounded steps in the network (Krishnamurthy et al., 2018; Gibard et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Acidic conversion of phosphoroaminonitrile to free aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals/montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"acidic phase, pH ~1.5\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"pH-triggered dephosphorylative conversion of the N-phosphoroaminonitrile to the corresponding aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step directly follows the literature summary: at pH 1.5, phosphoro-Strecker intermediates furnish aminonitriles. It is retained as a distinct node to avoid the overly compressed endpoint criticized in earlier attempts (Krishnamurthy et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis during geothermal cycling or prolonged residence in prebiotic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydration and hydrolysis produces the \u03b1-amino acid threonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the canonical completion step of Strecker chemistry. The literature summary explicitly identifies aminonitriles as threonine-relevant intermediates and hydrolysis as their productive fate (Strecker, 1850; Cleaves, 2010; Kitadai & Maruyama, 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis and deprotection of threonine aminothioamide to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry or pH-cycling conditions in prebiotic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminothioamide hydrolysis yields the corresponding amino acid under prolonged aqueous processing.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The phosphoro-Strecker literature identifies aminothioamides as productive downstream intermediates. Their hydrolytic conversion is a reasonable prebiotic completion route and is more faithful to the reported sequence than collapsing H2S and hydrolysis into one step (Krishnamurthy et al., 2018; Gibard et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Abiotic keto-acid route to 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated pool chemistry; non-enzymatic carbonyl addition/transformation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Non-enzymatic carbonyl coupling of a hydroxy-ketoacid equivalent with acetaldehyde gives the C4 \u03b1-ketoacid precursor 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report highlights abiotic conversion of \u03b1-ketoacids as a plausible prebiotic route class and emphasizes glyoxylate/pyruvate-centered protometabolism. This threonine-specific C4 ketoacid step is more speculative than Strecker chemistry, but it is included because the literature explicitly points to \u03b1-ketoacid-to-amino-acid analogs as relevant and because it provides an alternative convergent route without compressing directly to threonine (Kitadai et al., 2018; Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Abiotic amination/transamination analog from 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous phosphate-rich pools; NH3/CN-assisted imine chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Imine formation at the \u03b1-ketoacid followed by reductive/assisted amination gives the corresponding amino acid threonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The knowledge base specifically identifies abiotic conversion of \u03b1-ketoacids with cyanide and ammonia as a proposed amino-acid-forming framework mirroring biological transamination. Direct demonstration for threonine is limited, so this endpoint is explicitly a plausible analog rather than a fully established threonine-specific experiment (Kitadai et al., 2018; Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct hydroxyaldehyde Strecker from hydrothermal aldehydes\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal aldehydes feed surface hydroxyaldehyde formation, followed by Strecker aminonitrile synthesis and hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic glycolonitrile route to Strecker threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface photochemistry converts hydrothermal formaldehyde into glycolonitrile and then a hydroxyaldehyde pool that enters Strecker chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker to aminonitrile then hydrolysis\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydroxyaldehyde precursor enters phosphoro-Strecker chemistry, then acidic conversion gives the free aminonitrile which hydrolyzes to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker via aminothioamide\",\n      \"description\": \"The phosphoro-Strecker intermediate is diverted through the H2S-mediated aminothioamide route before hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal protometabolic keto-acid route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation yields glyoxylate and pyruvate, which feed a hydroxy-ketoacid branch to a C4 ketoacid and then abiotic amination to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Mixed aldehyde and keto-acid convergence\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal aldehydes generate acetaldehyde while hydrothermal protometabolism supplies hydroxypyruvate; these converge on 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate before amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Feedstock-to-HCN-to-Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde and ammonia give surface cyanide/formamide feedstocks, which are then used for Strecker synthesis of the threonine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Feedstock-to-HCN-to-phosphoro-Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"The same hydrothermal-to-surface feedstock transfer supplies cyanide for phosphoro-Strecker formation and aminonitrile hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic to phosphoro-Strecker hybrid\",\n      \"description\": \"Glycolonitrile-based surface chemistry furnishes the hydroxyaldehyde precursor, which then enters phosphoro-Strecker chemistry and the aminothioamide branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical fully integrated route\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent carbon fixation supplies formate, glyoxylate, and pyruvate; surface UV chemistry furnishes HCN and hydroxyaldehydes; both streams converge through Strecker chemistry to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "This network builds threonine through literature-grounded route classes rather than a single asserted threonine-specific mechanism, because the research record indicates that exact threonine-forming prebiotic sequences remain unresolved. The network therefore centers on experimentally discussed precursor families and environments: hydrothermal generation of reduced C1/C2 feedstocks and protometabolic keto-acid hubs, surface Strecker and phosphoro-Strecker chemistry from aldehydes with HCN/NH3/DAP, cyanosulfidic production of hydroxy-nitrile intermediates, and biochemical/prebiotic completion by hydrolysis, transamination analogs, and wet-dry concentration. The threonine-specific branch uses 2-hydroxypropanal as the most chemically appropriate hydroxyaldehyde precursor for threonine-forming Strecker/phosphoro-Strecker chemistry, while explicitly noting that direct threonine-specific experimental proof is limited. Ten distinct pathways are provided as alternative traversals through the same connected bipartite network.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid/formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formalde